1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:01,000
 Amen.

2
00:00:01,000 --> 00:00:02,000
 Thank you, church.

3
00:00:02,000 --> 00:00:03,000
 Thank you, worship team.

4
00:00:03,000 --> 00:00:05,720
 That was a beautiful time.

5
00:00:05,720 --> 00:00:10,520
 As you sit down, maybe someone new sat down next to you as we've been worshiping.

6
00:00:10,520 --> 00:00:12,280
 You can say hello.

7
00:00:12,280 --> 00:00:13,820
 Let's be friendly, welcoming.

8
00:00:13,820 --> 00:00:18,120
 If you're joining us online, good to see you as well.

9
00:00:18,120 --> 00:00:20,880
 All right.

10
00:00:20,880 --> 00:00:27,600
 Well, good to see everyone this morning.

11
00:00:27,600 --> 00:00:32,320
 If you've been with us for a few weeks, you might know we've been walking through a sermon

12
00:00:32,320 --> 00:00:35,880
 series we've entitled Public Faith.

13
00:00:35,880 --> 00:00:40,560
 We've been talking about how to live a bit more publicly with the faith that we profess

14
00:00:40,560 --> 00:00:45,480
 to have in Jesus, how that actually makes a difference in the way we live our lives.

15
00:00:45,480 --> 00:00:48,040
 Today the topic is relationships.

16
00:00:48,040 --> 00:00:52,780
 We're talking about relationships today.

17
00:00:52,780 --> 00:00:58,160
 If I did a little survey of everybody, probably most of you, 90 something percent probably

18
00:00:58,160 --> 00:01:03,280
 I would say would have some sort of a social media on your phone or your computer.

19
00:01:03,280 --> 00:01:08,360
 You're involved in some way, Instagram or WeChat or whatever it is.

20
00:01:08,360 --> 00:01:12,320
 There's some kind of social media that you have.

21
00:01:12,320 --> 00:01:16,160
 But before we had all these platforms today, I'm going to take us back a little bit.

22
00:01:16,160 --> 00:01:20,660
 There was one, like the original social media platform.

23
00:01:20,660 --> 00:01:22,820
 This is the place where I lived.

24
00:01:22,820 --> 00:01:26,300
 This was a time of dial up internet.

25
00:01:26,300 --> 00:01:27,360
 Some of you remember that, right?

26
00:01:27,360 --> 00:01:31,660
 When you would log into internet and you'd be like, "Eee, eee, eee, eee, eee."

27
00:01:31,660 --> 00:01:36,620
 Sounds like a cat dying before you could like log on to the World Wide Web.

28
00:01:36,620 --> 00:01:41,460
 And once you were online, you'd have to pray that nobody called the home phone because

29
00:01:41,460 --> 00:01:44,660
 if somebody called the phone and your mom picked up or something, it would disconnect

30
00:01:44,660 --> 00:01:48,220
 the internet and you have to start what you're doing all over again.

31
00:01:48,220 --> 00:01:52,140
 So there's two things I would do when I was online back then.

32
00:01:52,140 --> 00:01:55,180
 First was visit a website called LimeWire.

33
00:01:55,180 --> 00:01:56,900
 Does anybody know what LimeWire is?

34
00:01:56,900 --> 00:02:00,580
 Yeah, okay, Marcus is a dodgy guy, right?

35
00:02:00,580 --> 00:02:05,580
 LimeWire was, okay, it was, you could get music for free, okay?

36
00:02:05,580 --> 00:02:09,140
 Now, that's what people told me, okay?

37
00:02:09,140 --> 00:02:16,340
 But the next thing I would do is log into the internet to listen for a particular sound,

38
00:02:16,340 --> 00:02:18,900
 a sound that some of you might recognize.

39
00:02:18,900 --> 00:02:20,460
 It goes a little bit like this.

40
00:02:20,460 --> 00:02:23,580
 Do you remember that?

41
00:02:23,580 --> 00:02:24,580
 Right?

42
00:02:24,580 --> 00:02:30,500
 I just triggered every single millennial here in this place, okay?

43
00:02:30,500 --> 00:02:33,820
 Every time I hear that, okay, I'm immediately taking...

44
00:02:33,820 --> 00:02:37,900
 Oh, there you go.

45
00:02:37,900 --> 00:02:41,020
 Every time I hear that noise, it's pre-Teen Ellison, okay?

46
00:02:41,020 --> 00:02:42,740
 I'm taking right away.

47
00:02:42,740 --> 00:02:46,460
 I'm sitting at my home computer, which is in the living room, okay?

48
00:02:46,460 --> 00:02:50,000
 It's got like the massive box of a monitor, right?

49
00:02:50,000 --> 00:02:51,000
 Making all this noise.

50
00:02:51,000 --> 00:02:55,820
 It's late at night, and it's just me and the warm glow of the giant monitor that's in front

51
00:02:55,820 --> 00:02:56,820
 of me, right?

52
00:02:56,820 --> 00:03:01,100
 And the sound you just heard was from a platform called iSeekU, right?

53
00:03:01,100 --> 00:03:02,820
 iSeekU, right?

54
00:03:02,820 --> 00:03:04,500
 The original social media platform.

55
00:03:04,500 --> 00:03:08,860
 There was this instant messaging where you could, you know, log in and chat to your friends,

56
00:03:08,860 --> 00:03:12,940
 but you could also connect to random people all over the world, right?

57
00:03:12,940 --> 00:03:15,660
 Super fun, lots of different things you could do.

58
00:03:15,660 --> 00:03:21,900
 So there would be, right, sign in to iSeekU, waiting for my school crush to message me,

59
00:03:21,900 --> 00:03:22,900
 okay?

60
00:03:22,900 --> 00:03:23,900
 Right?

61
00:03:23,900 --> 00:03:24,900
 You're just waiting on line, right?

62
00:03:24,900 --> 00:03:25,900
 Is she gonna log in tonight?

63
00:03:25,900 --> 00:03:26,900
 Is she not?

64
00:03:26,900 --> 00:03:27,900
 I don't know, okay?

65
00:03:27,900 --> 00:03:28,900
 It's a little bit exciting, right?

66
00:03:28,900 --> 00:03:30,580
 And when you get the, "Uh-oh," sound, right?

67
00:03:30,580 --> 00:03:33,740
 Yes, okay, I've received a message, right?

68
00:03:33,740 --> 00:03:34,820
 Yeah, right?

69
00:03:34,820 --> 00:03:38,140
 And so the girl I was crushing on at the time would send me a message, right?

70
00:03:38,140 --> 00:03:41,900
 Full of flutter of excitement would flow through the body, and there you were, like, chatting

71
00:03:41,900 --> 00:03:42,900
 away.

72
00:03:42,900 --> 00:03:45,140
 It was like you were on an online date almost, right?

73
00:03:45,140 --> 00:03:48,820
 And me and her, we would chat for hours on iSeekU, right?

74
00:03:48,820 --> 00:03:53,100
 Sharing our deepest secrets, declaring our puppy love to each other, right?

75
00:03:53,100 --> 00:03:55,980
 And I felt like, you know, I had a little bit of game on iSeekU, okay?

76
00:03:55,980 --> 00:04:01,460
 I was funny, I was clever, I was romantic, you know, a little bit cheeky maybe, but super

77
00:04:01,460 --> 00:04:02,460
 confident, right?

78
00:04:02,460 --> 00:04:06,660
 The kind of dude I would think that all girls want to talk to, like, stereotypically, I

79
00:04:06,660 --> 00:04:08,500
 guess, right?

80
00:04:08,500 --> 00:04:12,060
 Which was super confusing because when we went back to school the next day, things were

81
00:04:12,060 --> 00:04:13,220
 completely different, right?

82
00:04:13,220 --> 00:04:15,780
 I would see her at school, say, "Hey, Louisa," okay?

83
00:04:15,780 --> 00:04:19,540
 "Hi," her name was Louisa, "Okay, hi, Louisa, how's it going?"

84
00:04:19,540 --> 00:04:20,540
 Right?

85
00:04:20,540 --> 00:04:22,440
 It was so fun chatting to you last night.

86
00:04:22,440 --> 00:04:26,060
 And the response was, you know, just like, "Oh, what are you doing?

87
00:04:26,060 --> 00:04:27,220
 Like, why are you talking to me?"

88
00:04:27,220 --> 00:04:29,340
 It was like a scene of, you've seen the movie "Mean Girls," right?

89
00:04:29,340 --> 00:04:30,340
 It was a bit like that.

90
00:04:30,340 --> 00:04:33,080
 It's like, "Ew, like, why are you even talking to me?"

91
00:04:33,080 --> 00:04:37,400
 Maybe it's because back then I was, you know, 3'2" with like a super squeaky voice, right?

92
00:04:37,400 --> 00:04:41,560
 And she was like the pretty popular girl, and she just didn't want anything to do with

93
00:04:41,560 --> 00:04:42,560
 me in real life, right?

94
00:04:42,560 --> 00:04:43,560
 It's a bit sad.

95
00:04:43,560 --> 00:04:44,560
 No, it's okay.

96
00:04:44,560 --> 00:04:45,560
 It's okay.

97
00:04:45,560 --> 00:04:46,560
 It's okay.

98
00:04:46,560 --> 00:04:52,640
 I'm just telling you guys, this is my way of processing, all right?

99
00:04:52,640 --> 00:04:53,860
 Yeah.

100
00:04:53,860 --> 00:04:55,840
 But I realized something then, right?

101
00:04:55,840 --> 00:05:01,080
 I learned that actually online there was this weird power that you could have, right?

102
00:05:01,080 --> 00:05:02,800
 And a bit of a mystery, right?

103
00:05:02,800 --> 00:05:07,480
 You could be behind a screen and a keyboard, and suddenly you could be whoever you wanted

104
00:05:07,480 --> 00:05:08,520
 to be, right?

105
00:05:08,520 --> 00:05:13,640
 You could talk to whoever you wanted to and say whatever you wanted to say, but that didn't

106
00:05:13,640 --> 00:05:17,640
 always translate into what was happening in real life.

107
00:05:17,640 --> 00:05:23,080
 And as internet and social media platforms and all that stuff developed over the years,

108
00:05:23,080 --> 00:05:26,680
 things are super sophisticated now compared to back then.

109
00:05:26,680 --> 00:05:32,080
 The ability to be this other person behind a screen and a keyboard has only increased,

110
00:05:32,080 --> 00:05:33,080
 right?

111
00:05:33,080 --> 00:05:39,880
 And I would say in general, it's had some really bad and terrible impacts on our humanity

112
00:05:39,880 --> 00:05:41,560
 and especially our relationships.

113
00:05:41,560 --> 00:05:42,720
 It's not all bad.

114
00:05:42,720 --> 00:05:47,280
 Some fun things have come out of it as well, but in general, it's had a pretty bad impact

115
00:05:47,280 --> 00:05:48,280
 on our relationships.

116
00:05:48,280 --> 00:05:54,040
 Just look at some Instagram posts and just scroll through the comment section, right?

117
00:05:54,040 --> 00:05:59,440
 Sometimes something quite, you know, you would say was quite normal, just a normal post,

118
00:05:59,440 --> 00:06:07,480
 it's filled with like rude and mean and ugly, nasty, racist, sexist, judgmental, homophobic

119
00:06:07,480 --> 00:06:10,360
 comments all around, right?

120
00:06:10,360 --> 00:06:12,680
 Things that you would never say, right?

121
00:06:12,680 --> 00:06:17,240
 Horrible things that you would never say to a person face to face, suddenly because you're

122
00:06:17,240 --> 00:06:23,040
 online, you feel like there's no problem voicing your opinion.

123
00:06:23,040 --> 00:06:27,840
 Scientists call this the online disinhibitation effect.

124
00:06:27,840 --> 00:06:34,200
 And we feel bolder to say these wild things online because there is anonymity, right?

125
00:06:34,200 --> 00:06:35,440
 Nobody really knows who you are.

126
00:06:35,440 --> 00:06:40,400
 You can even create, and people do, right, fake accounts to comment on people's stuff,

127
00:06:40,400 --> 00:06:41,400
 right?

128
00:06:41,400 --> 00:06:43,680
 There's a sort of invisibility.

129
00:06:43,680 --> 00:06:48,680
 You can't really see the damage that you're causing to the other person receiving these

130
00:06:48,680 --> 00:06:49,680
 comments, right?

131
00:06:49,680 --> 00:06:54,560
 There's a...they call it the asynchronicity, which means that, you know, you can't see

132
00:06:54,560 --> 00:06:56,960
 it, and the timing of it, right, it's not immediate.

133
00:06:56,960 --> 00:07:00,840
 Like, if you're having a face to face comment, if I said something bad to Jackie, I could

134
00:07:00,840 --> 00:07:02,240
 see his reaction straight away.

135
00:07:02,240 --> 00:07:06,120
 But you can't see the other person on the other side.

136
00:07:06,120 --> 00:07:07,680
 Online is also like the Wild West, right?

137
00:07:07,680 --> 00:07:09,160
 There's no authority, right?

138
00:07:09,160 --> 00:07:10,760
 And what happens when there's no authority?

139
00:07:10,760 --> 00:07:12,560
 Well, people start wilding out.

140
00:07:12,560 --> 00:07:14,120
 They start doing whatever they want.

141
00:07:14,120 --> 00:07:16,680
 You just have to be a parent or a teacher, right?

142
00:07:16,680 --> 00:07:20,720
 Or maybe even in your office, or the boss goes away, the mics come out to play, right?

143
00:07:20,720 --> 00:07:29,280
 And so, all these things happen online, and they are terrible for our relationships.

144
00:07:29,280 --> 00:07:33,680
 On the other side of that, though, right, online, we also feel like that, actually,

145
00:07:33,680 --> 00:07:38,360
 you know, it's a place where we can only show good things.

146
00:07:38,360 --> 00:07:41,560
 No bad vibes or whatever people say, right?

147
00:07:41,560 --> 00:07:46,960
 And so, our social media spaces make it seem like life is, you know, stress-free, luxury

148
00:07:46,960 --> 00:07:52,680
 holidays, fast cars, nice clothes, beautiful people, fancy restaurants, well-behaved children,

149
00:07:52,680 --> 00:07:53,680
 right?

150
00:07:53,680 --> 00:07:59,160
 And it's like a highlight reel that we have to keep on conveying to the world.

151
00:07:59,160 --> 00:08:02,840
 Now, we all know this isn't reality.

152
00:08:02,840 --> 00:08:05,640
 Nobody really lives like that.

153
00:08:05,640 --> 00:08:11,760
 Everybody's lives are completely immune to stress, and brokenness, and struggles.

154
00:08:11,760 --> 00:08:18,600
 But when all we do is showcase the highlights of our life, right, we start to build barriers

155
00:08:18,600 --> 00:08:24,920
 in relationship because those kind of things, inevitably, start to build things like envy,

156
00:08:24,920 --> 00:08:29,760
 and jealousy, and even resentment with the people who are looking at it.

157
00:08:29,760 --> 00:08:36,480
 Now, as followers of Jesus, this online space that has been, you know, sort of growing up

158
00:08:36,480 --> 00:08:40,080
 with us, right, has been challenging.

159
00:08:40,080 --> 00:08:45,920
 It is challenging to sort of be a good Christian and know how to act online.

160
00:08:45,920 --> 00:08:52,000
 It's easy to get caught up in the negativity, start attacking others from behind the screen,

161
00:08:52,000 --> 00:08:54,320
 or to feel like we have to keep up with the Joneses, right?

162
00:08:54,320 --> 00:08:59,960
 So there's pressure that we have to make it look like life is perfect all the time.

163
00:08:59,960 --> 00:09:10,440
 And if we're not careful, our online selves can start to not resemble our relationship

164
00:09:10,440 --> 00:09:11,520
 with Jesus, right?

165
00:09:11,520 --> 00:09:16,980
 There's little evidence of our online selves that we are actually Christians.

166
00:09:16,980 --> 00:09:22,720
 And the danger is, in the most public space available for us to display our faith, sometimes

167
00:09:22,720 --> 00:09:25,480
 there's nothing to be seen.

168
00:09:25,480 --> 00:09:29,680
 And so even though we have this space where we're connected, you know, where we can basically

169
00:09:29,680 --> 00:09:34,880
 be connected to anybody in the world at any time, relationships are suffering in that

170
00:09:34,880 --> 00:09:36,840
 space.

171
00:09:36,840 --> 00:09:39,260
 But it's not just online.

172
00:09:39,260 --> 00:09:46,100
 It's also in our daily face-to-face personal relationships that are struggling as well.

173
00:09:46,100 --> 00:09:49,880
 As Andrew pointed out at the beginning of the series, right, we have been called to

174
00:09:49,880 --> 00:09:52,600
 be salt and light in this world, right?

175
00:09:52,600 --> 00:09:57,880
 And salt and light is what we're supposed to be as followers of Jesus.

176
00:09:57,880 --> 00:10:02,600
 We're supposed to be the ones who bring the flavor of Jesus, the flavor of God to a broken

177
00:10:02,600 --> 00:10:03,600
 world.

178
00:10:03,600 --> 00:10:08,560
 We're supposed to be the ones who shine the light of Jesus in the sinful and dark places

179
00:10:08,560 --> 00:10:10,640
 that we come across.

180
00:10:10,640 --> 00:10:14,360
 But when we do this, it means that we have to stand out.

181
00:10:14,360 --> 00:10:19,720
 It means that we have to fight for and believe in and speak up and act upon things that will

182
00:10:19,720 --> 00:10:23,480
 often go against popular culture.

183
00:10:23,480 --> 00:10:26,440
 And that's a hard thing to do.

184
00:10:26,440 --> 00:10:30,720
 And so instead, we feel the pressure to blend in.

185
00:10:30,720 --> 00:10:37,040
 We lose our saltiness, we dim our light, and we begin to conform to this world instead

186
00:10:37,040 --> 00:10:40,400
 of letting the power of Christ transform us.

187
00:10:40,400 --> 00:10:43,000
 And it plays out in many different ways, right?

188
00:10:43,000 --> 00:10:46,600
 Maybe you're at school, and at school there's a lot of parties, right?

189
00:10:46,600 --> 00:10:51,320
 People going out to parties, getting drunk, making terrible decisions, doing other stuff

190
00:10:51,320 --> 00:10:54,040
 that you know is wrong.

191
00:10:54,040 --> 00:10:58,080
 But you feel like you have to go along with the crowd and do what everyone else is doing.

192
00:10:58,080 --> 00:11:00,800
 Otherwise, you're going to be the odd one out, right?

193
00:11:00,800 --> 00:11:04,800
 You're going to be the Christian goody two shoes, the party pooper, and nobody wants

194
00:11:04,800 --> 00:11:07,920
 to hang out with anybody like that.

195
00:11:07,920 --> 00:11:13,960
 Or maybe you're in a relationship, in a romantic relationship, and there's increasing pressure

196
00:11:13,960 --> 00:11:17,680
 to be sexually intimate without or before getting married.

197
00:11:17,680 --> 00:11:20,680
 As culture would say, "Just go and enjoy each other.

198
00:11:20,680 --> 00:11:21,680
 It's only natural.

199
00:11:21,680 --> 00:11:23,600
 Everybody's doing it."

200
00:11:23,600 --> 00:11:32,400
 What kind of prude, corny, backwards, old-fashioned thinking is to think that sex is only reserved

201
00:11:32,400 --> 00:11:34,680
 for marriage?

202
00:11:34,680 --> 00:11:38,800
 Or maybe like Pastor Jennifer talked about the other day, at your workplace, in your

203
00:11:38,800 --> 00:11:45,280
 relationship with your colleagues and your boss, dishonest practices have become commonplace.

204
00:11:45,280 --> 00:11:46,840
 Nobody values the truth.

205
00:11:46,840 --> 00:11:50,520
 And if you don't follow suit, well, you're going to cost everyone their bonus.

206
00:11:50,520 --> 00:11:52,840
 You're going to affect the bottom line.

207
00:11:52,840 --> 00:11:56,920
 Who's going to want to work with a person like that, right?

208
00:11:56,920 --> 00:11:59,140
 And so here's the problem.

209
00:11:59,140 --> 00:12:03,760
 Because we want relationships, we feel like we need to conform.

210
00:12:03,760 --> 00:12:06,060
 We feel like we need to change who we are.

211
00:12:06,060 --> 00:12:11,000
 We feel like we need to compromise our faith and our values in Jesus.

212
00:12:11,000 --> 00:12:17,240
 And the more we do that, the more we change, we start to lose ourselves in the whole process.

213
00:12:17,240 --> 00:12:19,040
 We don't even know who we are anymore.

214
00:12:19,040 --> 00:12:21,160
 We don't even know our own identity.

215
00:12:21,160 --> 00:12:24,280
 Which version am I supposed to be in this situation?

216
00:12:24,280 --> 00:12:28,720
 The online self, the one at work, the one at church, the one in the gym?

217
00:12:28,720 --> 00:12:30,100
 I'm trying to fit in.

218
00:12:30,100 --> 00:12:34,480
 The more we try to fit in, the more we begin to lose ourselves.

219
00:12:34,480 --> 00:12:41,560
 But listen, if everybody's sort of doing this, if nobody's really being real with each other,

220
00:12:41,560 --> 00:12:47,120
 how are we ever going to have these meaningful relationships that we all crave?

221
00:12:47,120 --> 00:12:54,280
 And it's a huge problem because it goes against how God designed and created us to be.

222
00:12:54,280 --> 00:13:01,460
 Because the truth is, you and I and everyone else has been created in the image of God.

223
00:13:01,460 --> 00:13:08,100
 And in the way he made us to be was to have these deep, meaningful, genuine, life-giving,

224
00:13:08,100 --> 00:13:11,980
 joyful relationships with him and with each other.

225
00:13:11,980 --> 00:13:15,800
 There's no denying we've been created this way.

226
00:13:15,800 --> 00:13:18,420
 This is why everybody craves relationships.

227
00:13:18,420 --> 00:13:23,380
 If you go all the way back to Genesis, when God was doing his thing, creating the heavens

228
00:13:23,380 --> 00:13:27,860
 and the earth, after each day of work, he declared it was good.

229
00:13:27,860 --> 00:13:29,140
 If you remember the story, right?

230
00:13:29,140 --> 00:13:30,860
 Light and darkness, good.

231
00:13:30,860 --> 00:13:31,860
 Sky and land, good.

232
00:13:31,860 --> 00:13:33,860
 Sun, moon, planets, good.

233
00:13:33,860 --> 00:13:35,240
 Animals and fish, good.

234
00:13:35,240 --> 00:13:36,240
 Human beings, good.

235
00:13:36,240 --> 00:13:44,320
 At the end, God declared it was all very good, what he'd created, apart from one thing.

236
00:13:44,320 --> 00:13:47,020
 There was one thing he said that was not good.

237
